Provo Office

777 N 500 W Suite 102

Provo, UT

Click here for interactive map.

Location Summary

The defining feature of the Provo location is its proximity to Brigham Young University. Demographics, incomes, and age distributions all point to a population largely consisting of young, low-income, college students. While these factors do not typically suggest a strong market for dental professionals, the dense population and high concentration of other dental offices (strong referring potential) compensate for weaker indicators. Our market models suggest current demand to support slightly more than 1 additional oral surgeon in this location.

American Fork Office

1022 E 220 S Bamberger Dr

American Fork, UT

Click here for interactive map.

Location Summary

The American Fork location shows evidence of a dual population. Age distributions suggest a large segment of students, likely due to the proximity to Utah Valley University, and a substantial segment of working professionals with higher incomes and larger families. Population density appears to be far lower than in Provo, but is partially offset by higher growth rates and a higher concentration of dental professionals (strong referring potential). Though overall demand is not as high as in Provo, higher growth, larger incomes, more families, and fewer competitors suggest a healthy market. Our models estimate sufficient demand to support 1-2 additional oral surgeons in this location.

Saratoga Springs Office

2070 N Redwood Rd

Saratoga Springs, UT

Click here for interactive map.

Location Summary

Saratoga Springs is defined by small population, high growth, young families, and high incomes. Currently, our models estimate that the area is already oversaturated due to low population, few dental professionals, and excessive competitors. This is also partially due the locationâs proximity to mountainous, unpopulated terrain and Utah Lake. Demand is subject to change due to the high growth rate of large, high income households in the area combined with possible business from commuters that do not live in the area. While we would not strongly recommend expanding into this market at the present time, it definitely merits future consideration.

About Our Analysis Process

Optima Location Solutions employs a robust analysis process consisting of three parts:

1. Model development: We collect over 125 different demographic and economic variables. Each variable undergoes rigorous statistical analysis to assess which variables are predictive of successful practices in your market. Relevant variables are then used to create models that predict demand and models are statistically assessed for accuracy.

2. Estimate demand: Once a successful model has been developed, relevant demographic and economic variables are collected for your specific locations. These variables are combined with our predictive models to estimate market demand in each set of geography. Each location is assessed and demand estimates are reviewed to ensure that they are, indeed, relevant for you market and specific location.

3. Report development: Finally, we collect several notable demographic, economic, and market variables (such as competitors or symbiotic businesses) to present in a simple report format. We have taken painstaking care to present this information in a user-friendly format that presents actionable information and insights rather than a deluge of data and information. This also includes interactive Google Maps showing locations, areas of analysis, relevant data for each area, and competitor or other relevant business locations.
